{"type":"message","id":"426c90a9","parentId":"d94f8b96","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:20:37.091Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_012q8XEpUM9VUq4hkvrzefja","name":"read","arguments":{"file":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\s1\\s1_scene_director_contract.md"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_01GXHp2Vx3Px7R5UD4Lf5R2M","name":"read","arguments":{"file":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\workspace_mirror\\branches\\01_pre_production\\agents\\scene_director"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"anthropic","model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","usage":{"input":1,"output":159,"cacheRead":14548,"cacheWrite":529,"totalTokens":15237,"cost":{"input":0.000003,"output":0.002385,"cacheRead":0.0043644,"cacheWrite":0.00198375,"total":0.00873615}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775060432266,"responseId":"msg_01UMDemDnjXKy9euSuJdvai3"}}
{"type":"message","id":"1cb81992","parentId":"426c90a9","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:20:37.516Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"toolu_012q8XEpUM9VUq4hkvrzefja","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# S1 Scene Director Contract\n\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the role, boundaries, and file contract of the `scene_director` operator inside S1 (Pre-Production)._ \n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe `scene_director` is the S1 operator responsible for interpreting the script and transforming it into the first creative skeleton of the video.\n\nIts job is to convert script material into an editorially intentional sequence of scenes, defining scene boundaries and the narrative function of each scene in a way that gives the rest of the pipeline a clear structural base.\n\n---\n\n## Core responsibility\n\nThe central responsibility of `scene_director` is:\n\n> Transform the script into an editorially intentional sequence of scenes, defining the division and narrative function of each scene as the first creative skeleton of the video.\n\nThis means `scene_director` is not just a text splitter. It is the operator that gives narrative shape to the script at the scene level.\n\n---\n\n## Position inside S1\n\nWithin S1, `scene_director` is the first semantic/creative operator.\n\nIts output is the foundational scene structure that will later be:\n- validated\n- merged into canonical sector artifacts\n- used by downstream S1 steps such as polish and scene bible construction\n\n`scene_director` does not own the whole sector flow. It operates under S1 Supervisor coordination and explicit file contracts.\n\n---\n\n## Batch execution model\n\n`scene_director` does **not** receive the entire script in one call.\n\nInstead:\n- the S1 Supervisor uses `script_batch_planner` to split the raw script into manageable batches\n- batches are emitted in stable order (`sd_001`, `sd_002`, ...)\n- the supervisor uses `scene_director_io_adapter` to prepare an explicit payload for each batch\n- `scene_director` operates on one batch at a time\n- downstream deterministic logic merges batch outputs into canonical `screenplay.json`\n\nThis keeps batching, scheduling, and merge logic out of the operator itself.\n\n---\n\n## Input contract (current draft)\n\nFor each invocation, `scene_director` should receive a supervisor-prepared batch payload rather than the full script.\n\nThe payload should include, at minimum:\n- run/job context\n- batch identity (`sd_###`)\n- batch text\n- batch range metadata (`start_word`, `end_word`, `word_count`)\n- structural constraints relevant to scene generation\n- `scene_words_range` injected from channel config\n- explicit output path for the batch result\n\nThe operator should receive enough context to interpret the batch well, but should not be overloaded with unrelated downstream concerns.\n\n---\n\n## Boundaries / out of scope\n\n`scene_director` should **not** be responsible for:\n- planning script batches\n- deciding parallelism/concurrency strategy\n- merging batch outputs globally\n- validating sector completion\n- TTS polish generation\n- low-level file/path orchestration\n- final asset planning, prompt writing, or visual execution details\n\nIt also should not collapse into a purely mechanical splitter. Its role is semantic and editorial, but still bounded.\n\n---\n\n## Relationship with S1 Supervisor\n\nThe S1 Supervisor is responsible for:\n- preparing the batch payload\n- deciding when `scene_director` is called\n- scheduling batches with controlled parallelism\n- validating batch outputs before merge\n- deciding retry/fail/continue behavior\n- deciding whether a failed batch should be patched, repaired, regenerated, or aborted\n\n`scene_director` is responsible for producing the batch-level scene structure output expected by the supervisor contract.\n\n### Validation and correction loop\n- each `scene_director` batch output is a separately validatable unit\n- batch outputs must be validated individually before any global screenplay merge happens\n- if one batch fails validation, the supervisor should target only that batch rather than disturbing already-approved batches\n- validation policy belongs to the supervisor and its deterministic skills, not to `scene_director`\n- `scene_director` may be reinvoked with structured correction feedback for the affected batch only\n\n---\n\n## Output contract\n\nFor each batch, `scene_director` should write one batch-level JSON result containing:\n- batch identity/context\n- ordered batch scenes\n- no global merge responsibility\n\n### Batch-level structure (draft)\n- `batch_id`\n- `operator`\n- `scenes`\n\n### Required scene fields\nEach scene produced by `scene_director` should contain:\n- `scene_local_id`\n- `scene_title`\n- `scene_summary`\n- `narrative_function`\n- `narration_original`\n\n### Structural / traceability fields\nEach scene should also contain:\n- `start_word`\n- `end_word`\n- `estimated_scene_word_count`\n\n### Span coordinate rule\nFor `scene_director` outputs, `start_word` and `end_word` should be **relative to the batch**, not absolute to the full script.\n\nThis means:\n- each batch defines its own local word coordinate system\n- the first word in the batch is word `1`\n- downstream deterministic logic may later convert or enrich spans with global coordinates if needed\n\n### Output principles\n- scenes must be ordered\n- `scene_local_id` must be sequential within the batch\n- `narration_original` must preserve the original text assigned to that scene\n- scene boundaries must not overlap\n- scene coverage must account for the full intended batch span\n- global canonical `scene_###` IDs are not the responsibility of `scene_director`; they are assigned later by deterministic merge logic\n\nThis output should be rich enough to preserve the creative and structural value of the operator, while remaining narrower than a full `scene_bible` or downstream visual planning artifact.\n\n### Correction modes\n`scene_director` should conceptually support at least two invocation modes under supervisor control:\n- `generate` -> produce a fresh batch result from the batch payload\n- `repair` -> revise one previously generated batch result using structured supervisor feedback\n\nImportant: `repair` does not mean `scene_director` self-manages validation or retry policy. The supervisor remains the owner of:\n- validation\n- retry classification\n- accept/reject decisions\n- deciding whether a problem is patchable, repairable, or requires batch regeneration\n\n---\n\n## Quality bar\n\nA good `scene_director` output should:\n- break the batch into scenes that make narrative sense\n- assign each scene a clear narrative function\n- preserve original narration accurately scene by scene\n- maintain clean ordering and non-overlapping boundaries\n- avoid missing or duplicating source text\n- produce a structure that can be merged deterministically and developed further by downstream S1 steps\n\nLikely high-priority failure modes to guard against:\n- overlap between scene text spans\n- missing coverage of source text\n- duplicated coverage of source text\n- non-sequential `scene_local_id`\n- malformed or incomplete scene objects\n- `narration_original` drifting away from the actual source text for that scene\n\n---\n\n## Current status\n\nAt this stage, the contract establishes:\n- the mission of `scene_director`\n- its central responsibility\n- its position as the first semantic operator inside S1\n- its batch-based execution model under supervisor control\n- the current draft of its input contract\n\nThe next step is to refine the exact repair semantics and any field-level constraints needed for implementation.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775060437515}}
{"type":"message","id":"1ec08bc6","parentId":"1cb81992","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:20:37.518Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"toolu_01GXHp2Vx3Px7R5UD4Lf5R2M","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"status\": \"error\",\n  \"tool\": \"read\",\n  \"error\": \"EISDIR: illegal operation on a directory, read\"\n}"}],"details":{"status":"error","tool":"read","error":"EISDIR: illegal operation on a directory, read"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775060437516}}
{"type":"message","id":"f8bd3af3","parentId":"1ec08bc6","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:20:46.089Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_01RPcc9EDTodR8jypcipQWKb","name":"read","arguments":{"file":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\runtime\\s1\\scene_director_runner.py"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_01WLWW9Usmb9agXJ2Bj1HCsY","name":"read","arguments":{"file":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\runtime\\s1\\supervisor_skills\\scene_director_output_validator.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"anthropic","model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","usage":{"input":1,"output":155,"cacheRead":15077,"cacheWrite":1926,"totalTokens":17159,"cost":{"input":0.000003,"output":0.0023250000000000002,"cacheRead":0.0045230999999999995,"cacheWrite":0.0072225,"total":0.014073599999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775060437518,"responseId":"msg_019tV91UamAcXP2ZPALR7MZR"}}
{"type":"message","id":"770fecfe","parentId":"f8bd3af3","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:20:46.896Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"toolu_01RPcc9EDTodR8jypcipQWKb","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\"\"\"Scene Director Runner — LEGACY compatibility wrapper around the newer S1 batch flow.\n\nLEGACY STATUS:\n- This module remains only because the prototype entrypoint `runtime.s1.s1_start`\n  still imports `run_scene_director` / `save_screenplay` and legacy tests still depend on it.\n- It does NOT represent the canonical OpenClaw runtime architecture for S1.\n\nCanonical architecture now expects:\n- supervisor-owned batch planning\n- explicit IO adapter bridge\n- OpenClaw `scene_director` operator execution\n- per-batch validation\n- deterministic merge into canonical screenplay.json\n\nThis wrapper keeps older call sites functional while adapting them to a newer\nscene object shape expected by the supervisor skills/contracts.\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport json\nimport re\nfrom pathlib import Path\nfrom typing import Any\n\nfrom openai import OpenAI\n\n\n# Max words per chunk sent to the model\nCHUNK_TARGET_WORDS = 600\n\n\ndef run_scene_director(\n    script_raw: str,\n    job: dict[str, Any],\n    config: dict[str, Any],\n    model: str = \"gpt-4.1-mini\",\n) -> list[dict[str, Any]]:\n    \"\"\"Split raw script into structured scenes using the newer scene contract.\n\n    Compatibility behavior:\n    - still accepts the old prototype signature used by `s1_start.py`\n    - still chunks long scripts internally\n    - but now returns scene objects aligned with the newer S1 contracts\n    \"\"\"\n    words_min, words_max = config.get(\"scene_words_range\", [35, 75])\n\n    chunks = _split_into_chunks(script_raw, CHUNK_TARGET_WORDS)\n\n    client = OpenAI()\n    all_scenes: list[dict[str, Any]] = []\n    global_scene_counter = 0\n    global_word_cursor = 1\n\n    for chunk_text in chunks:\n        chunk_word_count = len(_normalize_text(chunk_text).split())\n        system_prompt = f\"\"\"You are the scene_director for S1 pre-production.\n\nYour job is to transform this script batch into an editorially intentional sequence of scenes.\n\nCRITICAL RULES:\n1. Use clean narrative scene boundaries. Do NOT cut mid-sentence unless absolutely necessary.\n2. Preserve EVERY SINGLE WORD of the input text in narration_original. Do NOT add, remove, summarize, paraphrase, or modify wording.\n3. The concatenation of all narration_original fields must reproduce the input text EXACTLY, word for word.\n4. Use batch-relative word coordinates. The first word in this batch is word 1.\n5. Do not generate global scene IDs.\n6. Do not do visual planning, prompt writing, asset planning, or TTS polish.\n7. For each scene, return:\n   - scene_local_id: sequential within the batch (scene_01, scene_02, ...)\n   - scene_title: short clear label\n   - scene_summary: concise summary of the scene's purpose/content\n   - narrative_function: the narrative role of the scene\n   - narration_original: exact source text for that scene\n   - start_word: batch-relative start word\n   - end_word: batch-relative end word\n   - estimated_scene_word_count: exact word count implied by the span\n8. No gaps and no overlaps between scene spans.\n9. Aim for scene sizes compatible with configured scene_words_range ({words_min}-{words_max}) when natural narrative structure allows.\n\nOUTPUT: Return JSON object with a 'scenes' array. Nothing else.\"\"\"\n\n        response = client.chat.completions.create(\n            model=model,\n            messages=[\n                {\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": system_prompt},\n                {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": f\"Transform this text batch into ordered scenes:\\n\\n{chunk_text}\"},\n            ],\n            temperature=0.1,\n            response_format={\"type\": \"json_object\"},\n        )\n\n        content = response.choices[0].message.content\n        parsed = json.loads(content)\n        chunk_scenes = _extract_scenes(parsed)\n        _normalize_chunk_scenes(chunk_scenes, chunk_text)\n\n        for scene in chunk_scenes:\n            global_scene_counter += 1\n            scene[\"scene_id\"] = f\"scene_{global_scene_counter:03d}\"\n            scene[\"source_batch_id\"] = None\n            scene[\"source_batch_scene_index\"] = None\n            scene[\"source_scene_local_id\"] = scene.get(\"scene_local_id\")\n            scene[\"global_start_word\"] = global_word_cursor + int(scene[\"start_word\"]) - 1\n            scene[\"global_end_word\"] = global_word_cursor + int(scene[\"end_word\"]) - 1\n\n        all_scenes.extend(chunk_scenes)\n        global_word_cursor += chunk_word_count\n\n    return all_scenes\n\n\ndef _split_into_chunks(text: str, target_words: int) -> list[str]:\n    \"\"\"Split text into chunks at sentence boundaries.\"\"\"\n    sentences = re.split(r\"(?<=[.!?])\\s+\", text.strip())\n    chunks = []\n    current_chunk = []\n    current_words = 0\n\n    for sentence in sentences:\n        word_count = len(sentence.split())\n        if current_words + word_count > target_words and current_chunk:\n            chunks.append(\" \".join(current_chunk))\n            current_chunk = [sentence]\n            current_words = word_count\n        else:\n            current_chunk.append(sentence)\n            current_words += word_count\n\n    if current_chunk:\n        chunks.append(\" \".join(current_chunk))\n\n    return chunks\n\n\ndef _extract_scenes(parsed: Any) -> list[dict[str, Any]]:\n    \"\"\"Extract scenes list from various model response formats.\"\"\"\n    if isinstance(parsed, dict):\n        if \"scenes\" in parsed:\n            scenes = parsed[\"scenes\"]\n            if isinstance(scenes, list):\n                return scenes\n        for val in parsed.values():\n            if isinstance(val, list) and len(val) > 0:\n                return val\n        raise ValueError(f\"Unexpected response: dict with keys {list(parsed.keys())}\")\n    if isinstance(parsed, list):\n        return parsed\n    raise ValueError(f\"Unexpected response format: {type(parsed)}\")\n\n\ndef _normalize_chunk_scenes(scenes: list[dict[str, Any]], chunk_text: str) -> None:\n    chunk_tokens = _normalize_text(chunk_text).split()\n    cursor = 1\n\n    for index, scene in enumerate(scenes, start=1):\n        if not isinstance(scene, dict):\n            raise ValueError(f\"Scene {index} is not an object\")\n\n        scene_local_id = scene.get(\"scene_local_id\")\n        if not isinstance(scene_local_id, str) or not scene_local_id.strip():\n            scene_local_id = f\"scene_{index:02d}\"\n        scene[\"scene_local_id\"] = scene_local_id\n\n        narration_original = scene.get(\"narration_original\")\n        if not isinstance(narration_original, str) or not narration_original.strip():\n            raise ValueError(f\"Scene {scene_local_id} has no narration_original\")\n\n        narration_tokens = _normalize_text(narration_original).split()\n        word_count = len(narration_tokens)\n        if word_count == 0:\n            raise ValueError(f\"Scene {scene_local_id} has empty narration_original\")\n\n        expected_tokens = chunk_tokens[cursor - 1: cursor - 1 + word_count]\n        if narration_tokens != expected_tokens:\n            raise ValueError(\n                f\"Scene {scene_local_id} narration_original does not match chunk source at words {cursor}-{cursor + word_count - 1}\"\n            )\n\n        scene.setdefault(\"scene_title\", f\"Scene {index}\")\n        scene.setdefault(\"scene_summary\", scene[\"scene_title\"])\n        scene.setdefault(\"narrative_function\", \"narrative progression\")\n        scene[\"start_word\"] = cursor\n        scene[\"end_word\"] = cursor + word_count - 1\n        scene[\"estimated_scene_word_count\"] = word_count\n\n        cursor += word_count\n\n    if cursor - 1 != len(chunk_tokens):\n        raise ValueError(\n            f\"Chunk scene coverage incomplete: covered {cursor - 1} of {len(chunk_tokens)} words\"\n        )\n\n\ndef _normalize_text(text: str) -> str:\n    text = text.replace(\"\\r\\n\", \" \").replace(\"\\n\", \" \").replace(\"\\t\", \" \")\n    return re.sub(r\"\\s+\", \" \", text).strip()\n\n\ndef save_screenplay(\n    scenes: list[dict[str, Any]],\n    video_root: Path,\n) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Save screenplay.json to b1_pre_production/.\"\"\"\n    output_dir = Path(video_root) / \"b1_pre_production\"\n    output_dir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)\n\n    path = output_dir / \"screenplay.json\"\n    screenplay = {\n        \"scene_count\": len(scenes),\n        \"scenes\": scenes,\n    }\n    path.write_text(\n        json.dumps(screenplay, indent=2, ensure_ascii=False),\n        encoding=\"utf-8\",\n    )\n    return str(path)\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775060446896}}
{"type":"message","id":"7662579f","parentId":"770fecfe","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:20:46.899Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"toolu_01WLWW9Usmb9agXJ2Bj1HCsY","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"from __future__ import annotations\n\nimport json\nimport re\nfrom pathlib import Path\nfrom typing import Any\n\n\nREQUIRED_TOP_LEVEL_FIELDS = {\n    \"batch_id\",\n    \"operator\",\n    \"scenes\",\n}\n\nREQUIRED_SCENE_FIELDS = {\n    \"scene_local_id\",\n    \"scene_title\",\n    \"scene_summary\",\n    \"narrative_function\",\n    \"narration_original\",\n    \"start_word\",\n    \"end_word\",\n    \"estimated_scene_word_count\",\n}\n\nERROR_SEVERITY = {\n    \"payload_unreadable\": \"fatal_contract_error\",\n    \"output_unreadable\": \"fatal_contract_error\",\n    \"invalid_top_level_shape\": \"fatal_contract_error\",\n    \"empty_scenes\": \"fatal_contract_error\",\n    \"missing_required_field\": \"structural_patch\",\n    \"duplicate_scene_local_id\": \"structural_patch\",\n    \"non_sequential_scene_local_id\": \"structural_patch\",\n    \"invalid_scene_span\": \"batch_repair\",\n    \"scene_overlap_detected\": \"batch_repair\",\n    \"missing_coverage_detected\": \"batch_repair\",\n    \"duplicate_coverage_detected\": \"batch_repair\",\n    \"narration_source_mismatch\": \"batch_repair\",\n    \"estimated_word_count_mismatch\": \"structural_patch\",\n}\n\nCLASSIFICATION_PRIORITY = [\n    \"fatal_contract_error\",\n    \"batch_regenerate\",\n    \"batch_repair\",\n    \"structural_patch\",\n    \"ok\",\n]\n\n\ndef validate_scene_director_output(\n    *,\n    batch_payload_path: str | Path,\n    batch_output_path: str | Path,\n) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    errors: list[dict[str, Any]] = []\n    warnings: list[dict[str, Any]] = []\n\n    payload_result = _load_json(batch_payload_path, error_code=\"payload_unreadable\")\n    if not payload_result[\"ok\"]:\n        return _fatal_result(\n            batch_id=None,\n            errors=payload_result[\"errors\"],\n            warnings=warnings,\n        )\n\n    output_result = _load_json(batch_output_path, error_code=\"output_unreadable\")\n    if not output_result[\"ok\"]:\n        payload = payload_result[\"data\"]\n        batch_id = _extract_batch_id_from_payload(payload)\n        return _fatal_result(\n            batch_id=batch_id,\n            errors=output_result[\"errors\"],\n            warnings=warnings,\n        )\n\n    payload = payload_result[\"data\"]\n    output = output_result[\"data\"]\n\n    batch_id = _extract_batch_id(output) or _extract_batch_id_from_payload(payload)\n\n    source_batch = payload.get(\"batch\") if isinstance(payload, dict) else None\n    if not isinstance(source_batch, dict):\n        errors.append(_error(\n            code=\"invalid_top_level_shape\",\n            message=\"Batch payload must include a 'batch' object\",\n        ))\n        return _finalize_result(\n            batch_id=batch_id,\n            errors=errors,\n            warnings=warnings,\n            scenes=[],\n            source_tokens=[],\n            expected_batch_id=_extract_batch_id_from_payload(payload),\n        )\n\n    source_text = source_batch.get(\"text\")\n    if not isinstance(source_text, str) or not source_text.strip():\n        errors.append(_error(\n            code=\"invalid_top_level_shape\",\n            message=\"Batch payload must include non-empty batch.text\",\n        ))\n        return _finalize_result(\n            batch_id=batch_id,\n            errors=errors,\n            warnings=warnings,\n            scenes=[],\n            source_tokens=[],\n            expected_batch_id=_extract_batch_id_from_payload(payload),\n        )\n\n    scenes = _validate_top_level_output(output, errors)\n    if not scenes:\n        return _finalize_result(\n            batch_id=batch_id,\n            errors=errors,\n            warnings=warnings,\n            scenes=[],\n            source_tokens=_tokenize_text(source_text),\n            expected_batch_id=_extract_batch_id_from_payload(payload),\n        )\n\n    _validate_batch_id_match(output, payload, errors)\n    _validate_required_scene_fields(scenes, errors)\n    _validate_scene_local_ids(scenes, errors)\n    _validate_scene_spans(scenes, errors)\n\n    source_tokens = _tokenize_text(source_text)\n    _validate_coverage(scenes, len(source_tokens), errors)\n    _validate_narration_fidelity(scenes, source_tokens, errors)\n    _validate_estimated_word_counts(scenes, errors)\n\n    return _finalize_result(\n        batch_id=batch_id,\n        errors=errors,\n        warnings=warnings,\n        scenes=scenes,\n        source_tokens=source_tokens,\n        expected_batch_id=_extract_batch_id_from_payload(payload),\n    )\n\n\ndef _load_json(path: str | Path, *, error_code: str) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    path = Path(path)\n    try:\n        data = json.loads(path.read_text(encoding=\"utf-8\"))\n    except Exception as exc:  # noqa: BLE001\n        return {\n            \"ok\": False,\n            \"errors\": [_error(error_code, f\"Failed to read JSON from {path}: {exc}\")],\n        }\n    return {\n        \"ok\": True,\n        \"data\": data,\n    }\n\n\ndef _validate_top_level_output(output: Any, errors: list[dict[str, Any]]) -> list[dict[str, Any]]:\n    if not isinstance(output, dict):\n        errors.append(_error(\n            code=\"invalid_top_level_shape\",\n            message=\"Scene director output must be a JSON object\",\n        ))\n        return []\n\n    missing_top_level = sorted(REQUIRED_TOP_LEVEL_FIELDS - set(output.keys()))\n    if missing_top_level:\n        errors.append(_error(\n            code=\"invalid_top_level_shape\",\n            message=f\"Output is missing top-level fields: {', '.join(missing_top_level)}\",\n        ))\n\n    scenes = output.get(\"scenes\")\n    if not isinstance(scenes, list):\n        errors.append(_error(\n            code=\"invalid_top_level_shape\",\n            message=\"Output 'scenes' must be a list\",\n        ))\n        return []\n\n    if not scenes:\n        errors.append(_error(\n            code=\"empty_scenes\",\n            message=\"Output 'scenes' list is empty\",\n        ))\n        return []\n\n    valid_scenes: list[dict[str, Any]] = []\n    for index, scene in enumerate(scenes, start=1):\n        if not isinstance(scene, dict):\n            errors.append(_error(\n                code=\"missing_required_field\",\n                message=f\"Scene at index {index} must be an object\",\n                scene_ids=[f\"scene_index_{index}\"],\n            ))\n            continue\n        valid_scenes.append(scene)\n\n    return valid_scenes\n\n\ndef _validate_batch_id_match(output: dict[str, Any], payload: dict[str, Any], errors: list[dict[str, Any]]) -> None:\n    output_batch_id = _extract_batch_id(output)\n    expected_batch_id = _extract_batch_id_from_payload(payload)\n    if output_batch_id and expected_batch_id and output_batch_id != expected_batch_id:\n        errors.append(_error(\n            code=\"missing_required_field\",\n            message=f\"Output batch_id '{output_batch_id}' does not match expected '{expected_batch_id}'\",\n        ))\n\n\ndef _validate_required_scene_fields(scenes: list[dict[str, Any]], errors: list[dict[str, Any]]) -> None:\n    for scene in scenes:\n        missing_fields = sorted(REQUIRED_SCENE_FIELDS - set(scene.keys()))\n        if missing_fields:\n            errors.append(_error(\n                code=\"missing_required_field\",\n                message=(\n                    f\"Scene {scene.get('scene_local_id', '<unknown>')} is missing required fields: \"\n                    f\"{', '.join(missing_fields)}\"\n                ),\n                scene_ids=[scene.get(\"scene_local_id\")],\n            ))\n\n\ndef _validate_scene_local_ids(scenes: list[dict[str, Any]], errors: list[dict[str, Any]]) -> None:\n    seen: set[str] = set()\n    expected_index = 1\n\n    for scene in scenes:\n        scene_local_id = scene.get(\"scene_local_id\")\n        if not isinstance(scene_local_id, str):\n            continue\n\n        if scene_local_id in seen:\n            errors.append(_error(\n                code=\"duplicate_scene_local_id\",\n                message=f\"Duplicate scene_local_id detected: {scene_local_id}\",\n                scene_ids=[scene_local_id],\n            ))\n        else:\n            seen.add(scene_local_id)\n\n        expected_id = f\"scene_{expected_index:02d}\"\n        if scene_local_id != expected_id:\n            errors.append(_error(\n                code=\"non_sequential_scene_local_id\",\n                message=f\"Expected {expected_id} but found {scene_local_id}\",\n                scene_ids=[scene_local_id],\n            ))\n        expected_index += 1\n\n\ndef _validate_scene_spans(scenes: list[dict[str, Any]], errors: list[dict[str, Any]]) -> None:\n    previous_end: int | None = None\n    previous_scene_id: str | None = None\n\n    for scene in scenes:\n        scene_id = scene.get(\"scene_local_id\")\n        start_word = scene.get(\"start_word\")\n        end_word = scene.get(\"end_word\")\n\n        if not isinstance(start_word, int) or not isinstance(end_word, int):\n            errors.append(_error(\n                code=\"invalid_scene_span\",\n                message=f\"Scene {scene_id} must have integer start_word/end_word\",\n                scene_ids=[scene_id],\n            ))\n            continue\n\n        if start_word < 1 or end_word < 1 or start_word > end_word:\n            errors.append(_error(\n                code=\"invalid_scene_span\",\n                message=f\"Scene {scene_id} has invalid span ({start_word}-{end_word})\",\n                scene_ids=[scene_id],\n            ))\n            continue\n\n        if previous_end is not None and start_word <= previous_end:\n            errors.append(_error(\n                code=\"scene_overlap_detected\",\n                message=(\n                    f\"Scene {scene_id} overlaps with {previous_scene_id} \"\n                    f\"({start_word} <= previous end {previous_end})\"\n                ),\n                scene_ids=[previous_scene_id, scene_id],\n            ))\n\n        previous_end = end_word\n        previous_scene_id = scene_id\n\n\ndef _validate_coverage(scenes: list[dict[str, Any]], source_word_count: int, errors: list[dict[str, Any]]) -> None:\n    if source_word_count == 0:\n        return\n\n    coverage = [0] * source_word_count\n\n    for scene in scenes:\n        start_word = scene.get(\"start_word\")\n        end_word = scene.get(\"end_word\")\n        scene_id = scene.get(\"scene_local_id\")\n\n        if not isinstance(start_word, int) or not isinstance(end_word, int):\n            continue\n        if start_word < 1 or end_word > source_word_count or start_word > end_word:\n            errors.append(_error(\n                code=\"invalid_scene_span\",\n                message=(\n                    f\"Scene {scene_id} span ({start_word}-{end_word}) is outside batch-relative range \"\n                    f\"1-{source_word_count}\"\n                ),\n                scene_ids=[scene_id],\n            ))\n            continue\n\n        for index in range(start_word - 1, end_word):\n            coverage[index] += 1\n\n    missing_ranges = _collect_ranges([i + 1 for i, count in enumerate(coverage) if count == 0])\n    duplicate_ranges = _collect_ranges([i + 1 for i, count in enumerate(coverage) if count > 1])\n\n    for start_word, end_word in missing_ranges:\n        errors.append(_error(\n            code=\"missing_coverage_detected\",\n            message=f\"Words {start_word}-{end_word} are not assigned to any scene\",\n        ))\n\n    for start_word, end_word in duplicate_ranges:\n        errors.append(_error(\n            code=\"duplicate_coverage_detected\",\n            message=f\"Words {start_word}-{end_word} are assigned to multiple scenes\",\n        ))\n\n\ndef _validate_narration_fidelity(\n    scenes: list[dict[str, Any]],\n    source_tokens: list[str],\n    errors: list[dict[str, Any]],\n) -> None:\n    for scene in scenes:\n        scene_id = scene.get(\"scene_local_id\")\n        start_word = scene.get(\"start_word\")\n        end_word = scene.get(\"end_word\")\n        narration_original = scene.get(\"narration_original\")\n\n        if not isinstance(start_word, int) or not isinstance(end_word, int):\n            continue\n        if not isinstance(narration_original, str):\n            continue\n        if start_word < 1 or end_word > len(source_tokens) or start_word > end_word:\n            continue\n\n        source_span_text = \" \".join(source_tokens[start_word - 1:end_word])\n        if _normalize_text(narration_original) != _normalize_text(source_span_text):\n            errors.append(_error(\n                code=\"narration_source_mismatch\",\n                message=f\"Scene {scene_id} narration_original does not match source span {start_word}-{end_word}\",\n                scene_ids=[scene_id],\n            ))\n\n\ndef _validate_estimated_word_counts(scenes: list[dict[str, Any]], errors: list[dict[str, Any]]) -> None:\n    for scene in scenes:\n        scene_id = scene.get(\"scene_local_id\")\n        start_word = scene.get(\"start_word\")\n        end_word = scene.get(\"end_word\")\n        estimated_scene_word_count = scene.get(\"estimated_scene_word_count\")\n\n        if not isinstance(start_word, int) or not isinstance(end_word, int):\n            continue\n        if not isinstance(estimated_scene_word_count, int):\n            errors.append(_error(\n                code=\"estimated_word_count_mismatch\",\n                message=f\"Scene {scene_id} must have integer estimated_scene_word_count\",\n                scene_ids=[scene_id],\n            ))\n            continue\n\n        actual_count = end_word - start_word + 1\n        if estimated_scene_word_count != actual_count:\n            errors.append(_error(\n                code=\"estimated_word_count_mismatch\",\n                message=(\n                    f\"Scene {scene_id} estimated_scene_word_count={estimated_scene_word_count} \"\n                    f\"but span implies {actual_count}\"\n                ),\n                scene_ids=[scene_id],\n            ))\n\n\ndef _tokenize_text(text: str) -> list[str]:\n    normalized = _normalize_text(text)\n    if not normalized:\n        return []\n    return normalized.split(\" \")\n\n\ndef _normalize_text(text: str) -> str:\n    text = text.replace(\"\\r\\n\", \" \").replace(\"\\n\", \" \").replace(\"\\t\", \" \")\n    text = re.sub(r\"\\s+\", \" \", text).strip()\n    return text\n\n\ndef _collect_ranges(word_indices: list[int]) -> list[tuple[int, int]]:\n    if not word_indices:\n        return []\n\n    ranges: list[tuple[int, int]] = []\n    start = word_indices[0]\n    previous = word_indices[0]\n\n    for current in word_indices[1:]:\n        if current == previous + 1:\n            previous = current\n            continue\n        ranges.append((start, previous))\n        start = current\n        previous = current\n\n    ranges.append((start, previous))\n    return ranges\n\n\ndef _extract_batch_id(output: dict[str, Any]) -> str | None:\n    batch_id = output.get(\"batch_id\")\n    return batch_id if isinstance(batch_id, str) and batch_id.strip() else None\n\n\ndef _extract_batch_id_from_payload(payload: dict[str, Any]) -> str | None:\n    batch = payload.get(\"batch\") if isinstance(payload, dict) else None\n    if not isinstance(batch, dict):\n        return None\n    batch_id = batch.get(\"batch_id\")\n    return batch_id if isinstance(batch_id, str) and batch_id.strip() else None\n\n\ndef _error(\n    code: str,\n    message: str,\n    *,\n    scene_ids: list[str | None] | None = None,\n) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    clean_scene_ids = [scene_id for scene_id in (scene_ids or []) if scene_id]\n    payload: dict[str, Any] = {\n        \"code\": code,\n        \"message\": message,\n    }\n    if clean_scene_ids:\n        payload[\"scene_ids\"] = clean_scene_ids\n    return payload\n\n\ndef _fatal_result(\n    *,\n    batch_id: str | None,\n    errors: list[dict[str, Any]],\n    warnings: list[dict[str, Any]],\n) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    return {\n        \"ok\": False,\n        \"approved_for_merge\": False,\n        \"batch_id\": batch_id,\n        \"classification\": \"fatal_contract_error\",\n        \"errors\": errors,\n        \"warnings\": warnings,\n        \"stats\": {\n            \"scene_count\": 0,\n            \"source_word_count\": 0,\n            \"covered_word_count\": 0,\n        },\n    }\n\n\ndef _finalize_result(\n    *,\n    batch_id: str | None,\n    errors: list[dict[str, Any]],\n    warnings: list[dict[str, Any]],\n    scenes: list[dict[str, Any]],\n    source_tokens: list[str],\n    expected_batch_id: str | None,\n) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    classification = _classify_errors(errors)\n    covered_word_count = _compute_covered_word_count(scenes, len(source_tokens))\n\n    if batch_id is None:\n        batch_id = expected_batch_id\n\n    return {\n        \"ok\": classification == \"ok\",\n        \"approved_for_merge\": classification == \"ok\",\n        \"batch_id\": batch_id,\n        \"classification\": classification,\n        \"errors\": errors,\n        \"warnings\": warnings,\n        \"stats\": {\n            \"scene_count\": len(scenes),\n            \"source_word_count\": len(source_tokens),\n            \"covered_word_count\": covered_word_count,\n        },\n    }\n\n\ndef _classify_errors(errors: list[dict[str, Any]]) -> str:\n    if not errors:\n        return \"ok\"\n\n    severities = [ERROR_SEVERITY.get(error.get(\"code\"), \"fatal_contract_error\") for error in errors]\n\n    if \"fatal_contract_error\" in severities:\n        return \"fatal_contract_error\"\n\n    repair_like_count = sum(1 for severity in severities if severity == \"batch_repair\")\n    if repair_like_count >= 3:\n        return \"batch_regenerate\"\n    if repair_like_count >= 1:\n        return \"batch_repair\"\n    if \"structural_patch\" in severities:\n        return \"structural_patch\"\n\n    for classification in CLASSIFICATION_PRIORITY:\n        if classification in severities:\n            return classification\n\n    return \"fatal_contract_error\"\n\n\ndef _compute_covered_word_count(scenes: list[dict[str, Any]], source_word_count: int) -> int:\n    if source_word_count <= 0:\n        return 0\n\n    covered: set[int] = set()\n    for scene in scenes:\n        start_word = scene.get(\"start_word\")\n        end_word = scene.get(\"end_word\")\n        if not isinstance(start_word, int) or not isinstance(end_word, int):\n            continue\n        if start_word < 1 or end_word < 1 or start_word > end_word:\n            continue\n        for index in range(max(1, start_word), min(source_word_count, end_word) + 1):\n            covered.add(index)\n\n    return len(covered)\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775060446898}}
{"type":"message","id":"c4574778","parentId":"7662579f","timestamp":"2026-04-01T16:21:43.735Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. Let me analyze what's happening and whether the current design demands too much precision from the semantic agent.\n\nKey observations:\n\n1. **What the agent is currently asked to emit:**\n   - `start_word` / `end_word` (batch-relative integer coordinates)\n   - `estimated_scene_word_count` (must match span exactly)\n   - `narration_original` (must EXACTLY match the source text for that span)\n\n2. **The validator checks:**\n   - `narration_source_mismatch`: narration_original must equal the exact source tokens at `start_word`-`end_word`\n   - `scene_overlap_detected`, `missing_coverage_detected`, `duplicate_coverage_detected`: spans must perfectly tile the source text\n   - `estimated_word_count_mismatch`: must equal span exactly\n\n3. **The runner's `_normalize_chunk_scenes`:**\n   - Already **overrides** `start_word`/`end_word` deterministically based on `narration_original`\n   - So the runner actually IGNORES the agent's span numbers and derives them from narration_original position in the chunk\n\nThis reveals the core tension: the runner implements a hybrid approach where `narration_original` is the source of truth and span coordinates are derived from it, yet the validator still enforces strict matching on those coordinates as if they were primary inputs.\n\nThe real question is whether the agent should emit just `narration_original` and let deterministic code calculate the spans, or emit all three fields and accept strict validation. The agent's actual creative work is deciding where scene boundaries fall narratively—once that grouping is determined, the spans and word counts follow mechanically. Right now the agent is doing redundant work: deciding grouping, copying exact text, calculating spans, and deriving word counts, when really only the first step requires semantic judgment.\n\nThe validation is fragile because LLMs naturally paraphrase even when instructed not to, causing `narration_source_mismatch` errors. A cleaner approach would have the agent emit just enough information to identify the grouping—either the exact narration text (which still requires fuzzy matching to find in source) or the span boundaries directly (which the code can then validate against the source).\n\nThe most practical path forward is letting the agent emit approximate `narration_original` text that gets fuzzy-matched to the source, with deterministic code snapping boundaries to exact sentence limits. Alternatively, the agent could emit only metadata like scene titles and a rough end-word hint, letting the code derive all exact coordinates deterministically—though this trades some precision for robustness.\n\nThe real insight is that asking a creative agent to simultaneously handle semantic grouping *and* mechanical precision like perfect text copying and word counting creates unnecessary friction. Shifting the burden to deterministic code for exact spans while the agent focuses on the conceptual structure would dramatically reduce validation failures and retry loops.","thinkingSignature":""},{"type":"text","text":"Based on my analysis of the contract, runner, and validator, here's my assessment:\n\n---\n\n## Research Summary: S1 Scene Director — Precision Demands vs. Deterministic Derivation\n\n### What the agent is currently asked to do\n\nThe `scene_director` operator must emit **three kinds of outputs simultaneously**:\n\n1. **Semantic/creative outputs** — `scene_title`, `scene_summary`, `narrative_function` (agent's real job)\n2. **Exact text copying** — `narration_original` must be a character-perfect slice of source text\n3. **Exact numeric coordinates** — `start_word`/`end_word` (batch-relative), `estimated_scene_word_count` that must exactly match the span\n\n### The critical insight from the runner\n\n`_normalize_chunk_scenes()` in `scene_director_runner.py` **already ignores the agent's span numbers** and re-derives them deterministically from `narration_original`:\n\n```python\nscene[\"start_word\"] = cursor\nscene[\"end_word\"] = cursor + word_count - 1\nscene[\"estimated_scene_word_count\"] = word_count\n```\n\nSo the legacy runner has already partially solved this — it trusts `narration_original` and throws away the agent's span coordinates. But the **validator contract** (for the canonical OpenClaw operator) still requires the agent to emit valid spans AND valid narration AND they must match each other.\n\n### What's being demanded from a semantic agent\n\nThe validator enforces:\n- `narration_source_mismatch` → narration must exactly equal `source_tokens[start_word-1:end_word]`\n- `scene_overlap_detected` / `missing_coverage_detected` / `duplicate_coverage_detected` → spans must perfectly tile the source\n- `estimated_word_count_mismatch` → must equal `end_word - start_word + 1` exactly\n\nThis conflates two fundamentally different tasks:\n- **Creative task**: decide where scene breaks should fall narratively\n- **Mechanical task**: count words perfectly, copy text verbatim, emit consistent coordinates\n\nLLMs are unreliable at exact mechanical tasks under creative load. They paraphrase even when told not to, miscalculate word positions, and hallucinate span numbers.\n\n### Is this too much precision? Yes.\n\nThe design is demanding because:\n\n1. **Narration fidelity is fragile** — `narration_source_mismatch` is likely the most common failure mode. Even with temperature=0.1 and explicit instructions, models slip into light paraphrasing.\n\n2. **Spans are fully derivable from narration** — if you trust `narration_original`, `start_word`/`end_word`/`estimated_scene_word_count` are all deterministic lookups into the source text. The agent adds zero value by emitting them.\n\n3. **Narration is derivable from spans** — conversely, if the agent emitted only span boundaries (or just a scene boundary word index), `narration_original` is a trivial slice. The agent adds zero value by copying text.\n\n4. **The agent is doing both, but neither well** — it's being asked to copy text AND count words AND be creative. The repair loop exists because this fails.\n\n### Better design: agent decides grouping, code derives everything else\n\n**Proposed pattern:**\n\nThe agent emits only the creative outputs + a **grouping signal**:\n- `scene_local_id`\n- `scene_title`\n- `scene_summary`\n- `narrative_function`\n- `end_word` (batch-relative scene boundary) — OR just `narration_original` as an approximate anchor\n\nDeterministic code then:\n- Snaps boundaries to the nearest sentence boundary (prevents mid-word cuts)\n- Extracts `narration_original` as an exact slice\n- Derives `start_word`, `end_word`, `estimated_scene_word_count`\n- Handles coverage, overlap, and gap detection before the agent ever sees the output\n\n**Why this is better:**\n\n| Current Design | Proposed Design |\n|---|---|\n| Agent must count words exactly | Agent says \"break here roughly\" |\n| Agent must copy text verbatim | Code extracts text exactly |\n| Agent must emit consistent spans + text | Agent emits creative decisions only |\n| Validator detects mismatch, triggers repair | Fewer failure modes, less repair needed |\n| Mechanical precision demands crowd out creativity | Agent can focus on narrative grouping |\n\n**The grouping signal can be simple:** Just `end_word` as a soft hint, or better — agent emits `narration_original` as an *approximate* text block and code finds the best alignment via fuzzy matching (sliding window token comparison). This is exactly what the runner already partially does with its cursor logic.\n\n### Recommendation\n\n**Yes, the current contract is demanding too much precision from a semantic agent.**\n\nThe cleanest fix:\n1. Agent emits: `scene_local_id`, `scene_title`, `scene_summary`, `narrative_function`, and `narration_original` as an **approximate** text (not held to exact fidelity)\n2. IO adapter / deterministic skill performs **alignment**: finds where each narration_original best aligns in the source token stream (using longest-common-subsequence or sliding window), snaps to sentence boundaries, and derives all coordinates\n3. Validator validates the **deterministic output** (easy — it's always correct by construction), not the agent output directly\n\nThis reduces the agent's job to pure semantics (the creative decision of where scenes begin and end and what they mean), and pushes all precision requirements into deterministic code where they belong. The repair loop becomes nearly unnecessary for span/fidelity errors, preserving retries for genuinely bad creative outputs (wrong scene count, narrative function drift, etc.)."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"anthropic","model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","usage":{"input":1,"output":2389,"cacheRead":17003,"cacheWrite":7736,"totalTokens":27129,"cost":{"input":0.000003,"output":0.035835,"cacheRead":0.005100899999999999,"cacheWrite":0.02901,"total":0.06994890000000001}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1775060446899,"responseId":"msg_014dMPLBB7sKRsS5qK4LKPTX"}}
